Assignment 8: Classification Trees

Weâll be working with the âcarseatsâ dataset from the ISLR package. Run the code below to load the dataset into a dataframe (recall that âtidyverseâ dataframes are referred to as tibbles). Weâll then use mutate to create a Yes/No variable to indicate if carseat sales are high or not. We then delete the Sales variable from the dataframe.

carseats = as_tibble(Carseats) %>%
  mutate(High = factor(if_else(Sales <= 8, "No", "Yes"))) %>%
  select(-Sales)

The âcarseatsâ dataset is described here: https://rdrr.io/cran/ISLR/man/Carseats.html.

Q1 The variable types are correct and there is no missingness so we can go ahead and split the dataset. Use a random number seed of 999 and place 80% of the data into the training set. The response variable is âHighâ. How many rows are in the training and testing sets?

set.seed(999) 
car_split = initial_split(carseats, prop = 0.8, strata = High) #70% in training
train = training(car_split) 
test = testing(car_split)
  • There are 81 obs and 11 variables in the test data set and 319 obs and 11 variables in the train data set.

Q3 Use the Tidymodels framework to build a classification tree on the training set using the âCompPriceâ variable to predict âHighâ. Plot the resulting tree and describe how it would be interpreted.

carseat_recipe = recipe(High ~ CompPrice, train)

tree_model = decision_tree() %>% 
  set_engine("rpart", model = TRUE) %>% 
  set_mode("classification")

carseat_wflow = 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(tree_model) %>% 
  add_recipe(carseat_recipe)

carseat_fit = fit(carseat_wflow, train)
tree = carseat_fit %>%
  extract_fit_parsnip() %>%
  pluck("fit")  
fancyRpartPlot(tree)
  • From this tree you would interpret it by using the CompPrice >= 96 below the top figure. If your example fits that equation you would go left for yes/true and when you follow the dotted line you would see that according to the data your example is not high and that 97% of the data is also a no. This would be the same if your example did not fit the equation but you would go right meaing no/false and see that your example is high and only 3% of the data is a yes. Overall this is a simple tree to follow and would not be cumbersome.

Q4 Repeat Q3 but use all variables to predict âHighâ.

carseat_recipe2 = recipe(High ~ ., train)

tree_model2 = decision_tree() %>% 
  set_engine("rpart", model = TRUE) %>% 
  set_mode("classification")

carseat_wflow2 = 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(tree_model2) %>% 
  add_recipe(carseat_recipe2)

carseat_fit2 = fit(carseat_wflow2, train)
tree2 = carseat_fit2 %>%
  extract_fit_parsnip() %>%
  pluck("fit")  
fancyRpartPlot(tree2)
  • You would use this model the same as the previous one just there are more variable you have to follow but if your example satasifyies the equation go left and if it doesnât go right. Eventually you will reach the end to get your outcome. Overall while it is possible to use this chart it is tedious and cumbersome. Therefore, a higher chance of operator error can occur which makes this tree not ideal.

Q8 Try tuning the tree you built in Q4.This includes both the steps of unguided and guided tuning we discussed in class. Comment on both the steps.

set.seed(234)
folds = vfold_cv(train, v = 5)
carseat_recipe3 = recipe(High ~., train) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal(),-all_outcomes())

tree_model3 = decision_tree(cost_complexity = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine("rpart", model = TRUE) %>% #don't forget the model = TRUE flag
  set_mode("classification")

tree_grid3 = grid_regular(cost_complexity(),
                          levels = 25) #try 25 sensible values for cp

carseat_wflow3 = 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(tree_model) %>% 
  add_recipe(carseat_recipe3)

tree_res3 = 
  carseat_wflow3 %>% 
  tune_grid(
    resamples = folds,
    grid = tree_grid3
    )

titanic_recipe4 = recipe(High ~., train) %>% 
  step_dummy(all_nominal(),-all_outcomes())

tree_model4 = decision_tree(cost_complexity = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine("rpart", model = TRUE) %>% 
  set_mode("classification")

tree_grid4 = expand.grid(cost_complexity = seq(0.001,0.01,by=0.0001))

titanic_wflow4 = 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(tree_model4) %>% 
  add_recipe(titanic_recipe4)

tree_res4 = 
  titanic_wflow4 %>% 
  tune_grid(
    resamples = folds,
    grid = tree_grid4
    )
